  "location": "Wong Tai Sin Temple, Kowloon",
  "context": "Wong Tai Sin Temple (黃大仙祠) is one of Hong Kong's most visited temples, dedicated to the Taoist deity Wong Tai Sin. Visitors come to pray, consult fortune sticks (籤), and make offerings. A friendly local can show you the ropes.",
  "cultural_note": "Wong Tai Sin Temple (黃大仙祠) serves Taoist, Buddhist, and Confucian worshippers simultaneously, three traditions operating without apparent contradiction on the same site since 1921. The temple is Hong Kong's great home of kau cim (求籤, kau4 cim1), fortune-telling by shaking a bamboo cylinder of numbered sticks until one falls out, then matching the number to a printed oracle. Its reputation, 有求必應, \"every request answered\", keeps a whole arcade of soothsayers in business beside the main hall.",
